n context of labor organizing are key elements in the revitalization of the labor movement and the renewal of democracy. This book will allow the labor leaders of the future to learn from the recent experiences of their peers throughout the United States and Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzUnited States. 0aLabor movementzUnited States. 0aLabor unionszUnited States. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science.1 aCornfield, Daniel B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvans, Peter B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Lowell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172668240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501726682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501726682/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles